    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nUsing `nvim_open_win()` to create a window split can greatly increase the window size of the original window after splitting. This seems to happen when the requested size of the split window is larger than the original window. What happens in this case doesn't seem to be documented, but it's my (possibly naive) expectation that the original window doesn't enlarge.\n\n<img width=\"1360\" height=\"687\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/c926ba06-1939-458d-9316-8e8d67d193a0\" />\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nnvim -u NONE -c 'luafile repro.lua'\n\nrepro.lua:\n```lua\nlocal config1 = {\n    split = \"right\",\n    win = 1000,\n    width = 20,\n    vertical = true,\n}\nlocal config2 = {\n    split = \"left\",\n    win = 1001,\n    width = 20,\n    vertical = true,\n}\nvim.api.nvim_open_win(0, false, config1)\nvim.api.nvim_open_win(0, false, config2)\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nThe sum total width of windows 1001 + 1002  to grow, but the width of 1001 should be less than or equal to its width before the split.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.11.5\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nN/A\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nubuntu 24.04 (WSL)\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nwindows terminal/1.23.12811.0\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nsnap",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Likely a combination of equalization (#32854) and the workaround in #35601.\nYou may find the behaviour of `:set noea` more desirable here? (Or set `winfixwidth` for the two windows to better ensure they remain at their initially specified widths)\n\nUpon opening the 3rd window, the windows are equalized, but #35601 at least gives the 3rd window the correct size; before that PR all windows here would be sized incorrectly. (they'd all remain equalized)\n\nThat said, maybe it'd be nicer if the width was distributed in a more uniform way. (equally considering frames to the left _and_ right..?)",
